Here is a comprehensive guide to the C++ concepts you listed:

**Unit 3a: Basic Objects (Structs)**

### Introduction

In C++, a struct is a collection of variables of different data types that can be used to represent a single entity or object. Structs are similar to classes, but they are typically used for simple data structures.

### Defining a Struct

To define a struct, you use the `struct` keyword followed by the name of the struct and a list of variables enclosed in curly brackets `{}`:
```c
struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
    std::string address;
};
```
### Assignment of Objects

To assign one object to another, you use the assignment operator `=`:
```c
Person p1;
p1.name = "John";
p1.age = 30;

Person p2 = p1;
```
###. and -> Operators

The dot `.` operator is used to access the members of a struct object:
```c
p1.name = "Jane";
std::cout << p1.name << std::endl;  // prints "Jane"
```
The arrow `->` operator is used to access the members of a pointer to a struct object:
```c
Person* p = &p1;
std::cout << p->name << std::endl;  // prints "Jane"
```
### Use of getline()

The `getline()` function is used to read a line of text from the standard input stream `std::cin` and store it in a string object:
```c
std::string name;
std::cout << "Enter your name: ";
std::getline(std::cin, name);
std::cout << "Your name is: " << name << std::endl;
```
### Checking an Input Stream for Failure

To check if an input stream has failed, you use the `fail()` function:
```c
if (std::cin.fail()) {
    std::cerr << "Error: unable to read input" << std::endl;
}
```
### Using C++ String Class

The `std::string` class is a built-in C++ class that provides a convenient way to manipulate strings. You can use the `std::string` class to create, manipulate, and compare strings:
```c
std::string s1 = "Hello";
std::string s2 = "World";

std::cout << s1 + " " + s2 << std::endl;  // prints "Hello World"
```
**Unit 3b: Defining Your Own Classes**

### Introduction

In C++, a class is a collection of variables and functions that define the behavior of an object. Classes are similar to structs, but they have additional features such as encapsulation, inheritance, and polymorphism.

### public vs. private

In C++, access specifiers are used to control access to the members of a class. The `public` access specifier allows access to the members from outside the class, while the `private` access specifier restricts access to the members from outside the class.

```c
class Person {
public:
    std::string name;
    int age;

private:
    std::string address;
};
```
### Constructors and Destructors

Constructors are special member functions that are called when an object is created. Destructors are special member functions that are called when an object is destroyed.

```c
class Person {
public:
    Person(std::string name, int age) : name(name), age(age) {}
    ~Person() { std::cout << "Person object destroyed" << std::endl; }
private:
    std::string name;
    int age;
};
```
### Defining Member Functions

Member functions are functions that are defined inside a class. They can access the members of the class and can modify the state of the object.

```c
class Person {
public:
    void greet() {
        std::cout << "Hello, my name is " << name << std::endl;
    }
private:
    std::string name;
};
```
### Splitting Your Class into Files

To split your class into multiple files, you can use the `#include` directive to include the header file that contains the class definition, and then define the member functions in a separate source file.

```cpp
// person.h
class Person {
public:
    Person(std::string name, int age);
    void greet();
private:
    std::string name;
    int age;
};

// person.cpp
#include "person.h"
Person::Person(std::string name, int age) : name(name), age(age) {}
void Person::greet() {
    std::cout << "Hello, my name is " << name << std::endl;
}
```
**Unit 4a: Linked Lists**

### Introduction

A linked list is a dynamic data structure that consists of a sequence of nodes, each of which contains a value and a reference to the next node in the sequence.

### Implementing Basic Operations

To implement basic operations on a linked list, you can use the following functions:

* `push_back(value)`: adds a new node to the end of the list
* `pop_front()`: removes the first node from the list
* `pop_middle()`: removes the middle node from the list
* `pop_back()`: removes the last node from the list

```c
class Node {
public:
    int value;
    Node* next;
};

class LinkedList {
public:
    void push_back(int value) {
        Node* new_node = new Node();
        new_node->value = value;
        new_node->next = nullptr;
        if (head == nullptr) {
            head = new_node;
        } else {
            Node* current = head;
            while (current->next!= nullptr) {
                current = current->next;
            }
            current->next = new_node;
        }
    }

    void pop_front() {
        if (head == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        Node* new_head = head->next;
        delete head;
        head = new_head;
    }

    void pop_middle() {
        if (head == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        Node* current = head;
        while (current->next->next!= nullptr) {
            current = current->next;
        }
        Node* middle_node = current->next;
        current->next = middle_node->next;
        delete middle_node;
    }

    void pop_back() {
        if (head == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        if (head->next == nullptr) {
            delete head;
            head = nullptr;
            return;
        }
        Node* current = head;
        while (current->next->next!= nullptr) {
            current = current->next;
        }
        Node* last_node = current->next;
        delete last_node;
        current->next = nullptr;
    }

private:
    Node* head;
};
```
### Efficiency of Various Operations

The efficiency of various operations on a linked list depends on the implementation:

* `push_back(value)`: O(1) if the list is empty, O(n) otherwise
* `pop_front()`: O(1)
* `pop_middle()`: O(n)
* `pop_back()`: O(n)

### Pros and Cons Compared to Arrays

Linked lists have the following pros and cons compared to arrays:

* Pros:
	+ Dynamic memory allocation
	+ Easy insertion and deletion of elements
	+ No need to specify the size of the list
* Cons:
	+ Slow access and search times
	+ More memory usage due to the overhead of node objects

**Unit 4b: vector<T> and deque<T> Basic Operations**

### Introduction

The `std::vector` and `std::deque` classes are dynamic data structures that provide a convenient way to store and manipulate sequences of elements.

### Basic Operations

The `std::vector` and `std::deque` classes provide the following basic operations:

* `push_back(value)`: adds a new element to the end of the sequence
* `pop_back()`: removes the last element from the sequence
* `push_front(value)`: adds a new element to the front of the sequence
* `pop_front()`: removes the first element from the sequence

```c
#include <vector>
#include <deque>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> vec;
    vec.push_back(1);
    vec.push_back(2);
    vec.push_back(3);
    std::cout << vec.back() << std::endl;  // prints 3

    std::deque<int> deq;
    deq.push_front(1);
    deq.push_front(2);
    deq.push_front(3);
    std::cout << deq.front() << std::endl;  // prints 3
}
```
### Efficiency of Operations

The efficiency of operations on `std::vector` and `std::deque` depends on the implementation:

* `push_back(value)`: O(1) amortized
* `pop_back()`: O(1)
* `push_front(value)`: O(n) in the worst case
* `pop_front()`: O(n) in the worst case

**Unit 4c: Doubly Linked Lists**

### Introduction

A doubly linked list is a dynamic data structure that consists of a sequence of nodes, each of which contains a value and references to the previous and next nodes in the sequence.

### Implementing Basic Operations

To implement basic operations on a doubly linked list, you can use the following functions:

* `push_back(value)`: adds a new node to the end of the list
* `pop_front()`: removes the first node from the list
* `pop_middle()`: removes the middle node from the list
* `pop_back()`: removes the last node from the list

```c
class Node {
public:
    int value;
    Node* prev;
    Node* next;
};

class DoublyLinkedList {
public:
    void push_back(int value) {
        Node* new_node = new Node();
        new_node->value = value;
        new_node->prev = nullptr;
        new_node->next = nullptr;
        if (head == nullptr) {
            head = new_node;
            tail = new_node;
        } else {
            tail->next = new_node;
            new_node->prev = tail;
            tail = new_node;
        }
    }

    void pop_front() {
        if (head == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        Node* new_head = head->next;
        delete head;
        head = new_head;
        if (head!= nullptr) {
            head->prev = nullptr;
        }
    }

    void pop_middle() {
        if (head == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        Node* current = head;
        while (current->next->next!= nullptr) {
            current = current->next;
        }
        Node* middle_node = current->next;
        current->next = middle_node->next;
        if (middle_node->next!= nullptr) {
            middle_node->next->prev = current;
        }
        delete middle_node;
    }

    void pop_back() {
        if (head == nullptr) {
            return;
        }
        if (head->next == nullptr) {
            delete head;
            head = nullptr;
            tail = nullptr;
            return;
        }
        Node* current = head;
        while (current->next->next!= nullptr) {
            current = current->next;
        }
        Node* last_node = current->next;
        current->next = nullptr;
        tail = current;
        delete last_node;
    }

private:
    Node* head;
    Node* tail;
};
```
### Efficiency of Operations

The efficiency of operations on a doubly linked list depends on the implementation:

* `push_back(value)`: O(1) amortized
* `pop_front()`: O(1)
* `pop_middle()`: O(n)
* `pop_back()`: O(1)

**Unit 4d: Multidimensional Arrays**

### Introduction

A multidimensional array is a data structure that consists of a sequence of arrays, each of which contains a sequence of elements.

### Memory Layout

The memory layout of a multidimensional array depends on the language and the compiler:

* In C++, the memory layout of a multidimensional array is row-major, meaning that the elements of each row are stored contiguously in memory.
* In Fortran, the memory layout of a multidimensional array is column-major, meaning that the elements of each column are stored contiguously in memory.

### Passing Multidimensional Arrays to Functions

To pass a multidimensional array to a function, you can use the following syntax:

```c
void foo(int arr[2][3]) {
    // access the elements of the array
}

int main() {
    int arr[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
    foo(arr);
}
```
### Advantages of Passing by Reference

Passing by reference can improve the performance of function calls by reducing the overhead of copying the arguments.

### Const References

Const references can be used to pass objects by reference without modifying them.

```c
void foo(const int& arr) {
    // access the elements of the array
}

int main() {
    int arr[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
    foo(arr);
}
```
**Unit 4e: Syntax and Use**

### Introduction

The `std::ifstream` and `std::ofstream` classes are used to perform input and output operations on files.

### Syntax

The syntax for opening a file is as follows:
```c
std::ifstream file("filename.txt");
```
The syntax for closing a file is as follows:
```c
file.close();
```
### Use

To use the `std::ifstream` and `std::ofstream` classes, you can use the following functions:

* `open(filename)`: opens a file for reading or writing
* `close()`: closes a file
* `fail()`: checks if an error occurred while reading or writing a file
* `eof()`: checks if the end of the file was reached while reading a file

```c
int main() {
    std::ifstream file("filename.txt");
    if (file.fail()) {
        std::cerr << "Error: unable to open file" << std::endl;
    }
    char c;
    while (file.get(c)) {
        std::cout << c;
    }
    file.close();
    return 0;
}
```
### Checking for Failure

To check if an error occurred while opening a file, you can use the `fail()` function:
```c
if (file.fail()) {
    std::cerr << "Error: unable to open file" << std::endl;
}
```
### Checking for End of File

To check if the end of the file was reached while reading a file, you can use the `eof()` function:
```c
if (file.eof()) {
    std::cout << "End of file reached" << std::endl;
}
```
